<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Interest-rate hedging</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One question people have asked is: Why didn=E2=
=80=99t Silicon Valley Bank hedge its interest-rate risk? SVB, like other r=
egional banks, got a lot of deposits and invested them in long-term US gove=
rnment and agency bonds with fixed interest rates. As interest rates went u=
p, those bonds lost value, eating through all of SVB=E2=80=99s equity. This=
 was bad, people noticed, they withdrew their deposits, and SVB ran out of =
money. This was all pretty predictable, or at least a known risk. Why didn=
=E2=80=99t SVB hedge?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked about=C2=A0a couple of answers =
to that question:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SVB had expenses, and it needed to ma=
ke money. It had to invest its depositors=E2=80=99 cash to make that money.=
 In 2022, if it had been earning short-term interest rates on that cash, it=
 would not have made enough money to cover its expenses. <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1=
hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd2844c51" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  The way that i=
t made money</a> was by investing at long-term interest rates, which were h=
igher.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> So it invested in long-term bonds, earned higher rates, and made enoug=
h money. =E2=80=9CHedging=E2=80=9D would have meant swapping its long-term =
rates to short-term rates, which would have defeated its main purpose, maki=
ng money. And in fact SVB=C2=A0<em>did </em>have some interest-rate hedges =
in place in early 2022; it took them off, though, to increase its profits.=
=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SVB=C2=A0thought=C2=A0that =
it <em>was </em>hedged: It was=C2=A0buying long-term bonds, yes, but it was=
 funding those purchases with deposits. Those deposits are technically very=
 short-term: Depositors could take their money back at any time, and eventu=
ally they did. But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDkyM19NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIzMDUwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2146518=
8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  it is traditional in banking</a> to=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em=
>of them as long-term, to think that the =E2=80=9Cdeposit franchise=E2=80=
=9D and the deep relationship between banker and customer would make custom=
ers unlikely to take their money out. SVB invested a lot in good customer s=
ervice and good relations with its depositors; it also made loans to startu=
ps that=C2=A0<em>required=C2=A0</em>them to keep their cash on deposit at S=
VB. So it figured it had pretty long-term funding, and it matched that long=
-term funding with long-term assets. If it had swapped the assets to short-=
term rates, and then rates <em>fell</em>, it would lose money, and <em>SVB =
thought that was the bigger risk</em>. When SVB got rid of its interest-rat=
e hedges in early 2022, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L3B1YmxpY2F0a=
W9ucy9maWxlcy9zdmItcmV2aWV3LTIwMjMwNDI4LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e39=
a2f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> it did so=C2=A0</a><em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ29=
2L3B1YmxpY2F0aW9ucy9maWxlcy9zdmItcmV2aWV3LTIwMjMwNDI4LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cC7e39a2f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">because</a>=C2=A0</em>it had become =E2=80=9C=
increasingly concerned with decreasing [net interest income] if rates were =
to decrease=E2=80=9D: It worried that the hedges would hurt it if rates fel=
l.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those are, I think, the main answers. But ther=
e is one other sort of dumb accounting answer. Most of SVB=E2=80=99s intere=
st-rate risk came in its portfolio of =E2=80=9Cheld to maturity=E2=80=9D bo=
nds. The idea here is that SVB bought a lot of bonds and planned to hold th=
em until they matured. If it did that, the bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0which were =
mostly US-government backed and so very safe =E2=80=94=C2=A0would pay back =
100 cents on the dollar. So SVB didn=E2=80=99t need to worry about mark-to-=
market fluctuations in their value. If interest rates went up, and the valu=
e of these bonds dropped from 100 to 85 cents on the dollar, SVB could igno=
re it, because the value would definitely go back up to 100,=C2=A0<em>as lo=
ng as it held the bonds to maturity</em>. (The problem is that it=C2=A0<em>=
couldn=E2=80=99t:=C2=A0</em>There was a run on the bank long before the bon=
ds matured.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a standard assumption in banking, that=
 the bank is making loans or buying bonds and planning to hold them for lif=
e, so fluctuations in their market values don=E2=80=99t matter. And <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxk=
bi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmVkLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA5MjNfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yMzA1MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f2bf3f0=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">  bank=C2=A0accounting=C2=A0reflects this</a>: Held-to-maturity b=
onds are held on the balance sheet at their cost, and fluctuations in their=
 market values do not affect the bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet, or its incom=
e statement, or its regulatory capital. And thus for a while last year SVB =
was mark-to-market insolvent =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you subtracted its liabiliti=
es from the market value of its assets, you got a negative number =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but its regulatory capital was fine, because regulatory capital doesn=
=E2=80=99t subtract that way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now add hedging. SVB had, call it, $120 bi=
llion of held-to-maturity bonds. When rates went up, they lost something li=
ke $15 billion of market value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If SVB had fully hedged those bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it had put on $1=
20 billion notional amount of swaps, say =E2=80=94 then the hedges would ha=
ve perfectly offset that loss. But if rates had instead gone=C2=A0<em>down<=
/em>, the hedges would have lost money. Obviously last year rates probably =
had more room to rise than to fall, but even a 0.25% decline in long-term i=
nterest rates could have cost SVB something like $2 billion in this scenari=
o.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course in that scenario its bonds would hav=
e gained $2 billion of market value, offsetting the loss on the hedges. But=
 this is where the accounting is a problem. If you have a held-to-maturity =
bond, its fluctuations in value do not affect your income statement or bala=
nce sheet: When the market price of the bond goes up (or down), the book va=
lue of your assets does not go up (or down), and you do not have income (or=
 loss) from the change. But if you have an interest-rate swap, its fluctuat=
ions in value=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>affect your income statement and balanc=
e sheet: When its market value goes up (or down), the book value of your as=
sets goes up (or down), and you have income (or loss). An interest-rate der=
ivative is sort of naturally a mark-to-market asset, and so changes in its =
value are reflected in income.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if SVB had hedged and rates had gone do=
wn, it would have reported a huge loss: A $2 billion loss on interest-rate =
derivatives would have wiped out more than all of <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMDcxOTczOS8wMDAwNzE5NzM5MjMwMDAwMj=
Evc2l2Yi0yMDIyMTIzMS5odG0jaWJiNGRkNzNhMWQzZjRiZmY5NDRiNWQzNWZkMmM1ZTJhXzE4N=
w/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeab08c82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SVB=E2=80=99s profit last yea=
r</a>. Hedging the held-to-maturity bond portfolio would have made SVB=C2=
=A0<em>economically=C2=A0</em>less risky, but it would have made its=C2=A0<=
em>reported financial results=C2=A0</em>far more volatile. The hedge would =
have made SVB=C2=A0<em>look riskier.=C2=A0</em>And banking is a business of=
 confidence, so you don=E2=80=99t want to look riskier. (Also: The hedge wo=
uld have made SVB=E2=80=99s regulatory capital more volatile, and banking i=
s also a business of regulatory capital.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, an obvious response is: =E2=80=9CThis is =
dumb, why should hedging make you look riskier?=E2=80=9D And accountants ar=
e aware of that, and there is a thing called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly9mYXNiLm9yZy9=
kb2N1bWVudC9ibG9iP2ZpbGVOYW1lPUFTVSUyMDIwMjItMDEucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB26835520" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">hedge accounting</a>=E2=80=9D where you basically get=
 to take some asset and the derivative that you use to hedge it, offset the=
m against each other, and neutralize the accounting effect of fluctuations =
in their values. The hedge makes your financial statements look less risky,=
 which makes sense.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that this is=C2=A0<em>specifica=
lly not allowed for held-to-maturity assets</em>. <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly92aWV3cG9pbnQucHd=
jLmNvbS9kdC91cy9lbi9wd2MvYWNjb3VudGluZ19ndWlkZXMvZGVyaXZhdGl2ZXNfYW5kX2hlZG=
cvZGVyaXZhdGl2ZXNfYW5kX2hlZGdfVVMvY2hhcHRlcl82X2hlZGdlc19vZl9fVVMvNjRfaGVkZ=
2luZ19maXhlZHJhdGVfVVMuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdb4bce27" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 PricewaterhouseCoopers explains</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The notion of hedging the interest=
 rate risk in a security classified as held to maturity is inconsistent wit=
h the held-to-maturity classification under ASC 320,<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0which requires the reporting entity to hold the security until ma=
turity regardless of changes in market interest rates. For this reason, ASC=
 815-20-25-43(c)(2) indicates that interest rate risk may not be the hedged=
 risk in a fair value hedge of held-to-maturity debt securities.=C2=A0</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, here the accounting standards line up w=
ith the way banks have historically thought about themselves, which is basi=
cally that they are in the business of holding long-term assets for the lon=
g term. =E2=80=9CWhy would a bank hedge interest-rate risk on its held-to-m=
aturity portfolio,=E2=80=9D the accountants ask, =E2=80=9Cif it is just goi=
ng to hold that portfolio to maturity?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, you=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>hedge yo=
ur bonds that you treat as =E2=80=9Cavailable-for-sale,=E2=80=9D and if you=
 do that you will get hedge accounting treatment, so your income statement =
(and capital) will look less volatile rather than more. (This is <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
