<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Along these lines, I <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDgvb2lsLWNvbXBhbmllcy1naXZlLWJhY2=
stdGhlLWNhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC46cfb383" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a> that =
the main risk of banking comes not from its assets (bonds, loans) but from =
its liabilities: If you fund your business with short-term loans (deposits)=
 that can be withdrawn at any time, but you assume that your relationships =
with your lenders (depositors) are so good that=C2=A0<em>they </em>would ne=
ver withdraw their money, you are liable to get in=C2=A0trouble. And we hav=
e talked about the possibility that, in a mark-to-market, no-relationships,=
 Theory 1 sort of world, that funding model for banks wouldn=E2=80=99t work=
, or at least would become less popular. There is a set of ideas called =E2=
=80=9Cnarrow banking=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CChicago plan,=E2=80=9D in whi=
ch:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Deposits would not be used to fund loa=
ns or other long-term assets, but would just be parked at the Federal Reser=
ve: Banking would be fully reserved, bank accounts would just be dollars, a=
nd they would not be used to make loans.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Loans would be equity-funded: People who wanted to take credit (or i=
nterest-rate) risk would invest their money in funds, and the funds would m=
ake loans (or buy bonds). But the investors in those funds would not be inf=
ormation-insensitive bank depositors who expected access to their money at =
any time; they would be conscious risk-takers. They would know what they we=
re getting into: They would lock up their money for a long time and underst=
and that they were taking the risk of any loan losses. Loans would effectiv=
ely come from loan mutual funds, not from banks.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjAvYmFua2luZy1nZXRzLWEtYml0LW5hcnJvd2VyP2NtcGlkPUJCR=
DA1MDkyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVy=
JnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB1edf5f25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">  have suggested</a> that some of this is really hap=
pening now. For one thing, a lot of US money market funds <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMzAvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLW=
hhcy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbGw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwOTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZ=
Gl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTA5JnV0bV9jYW1w=
YWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9506d8af" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  kind of l=
ook like narrow banks</a> (they just park money at the Fed=E2=80=99s revers=
e repo program), while there has been a huge rise in private credit funds t=
hat=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>equity-funded lenders, and that are displacing b=
anks in some lending markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked yesterday about a <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0=
aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8wNS8wNi9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9iYW5rLWNyaXNpcy1zaGFkb3c=
tYmFua3MuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB310ec25f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> DealBook story<=
/a> about the rise of private credit, which worried that private credit fun=
ds are =E2=80=9Cnot subject to the same regulations as banks, which allows =
them to take greater risks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I thought that was the wrong thin=
g to worry about; I wrote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A private credit firm that raises =
money from investors in a locked-up fund, and uses that money to make idiot=
ic loans that all go bust, is <em>less </em>risky than, well, a licensed ba=
nk that raises money from uninsured depositors and uses that money to buy s=
afe US-government-backed bonds, like Silicon Valley Bank did.</p></blockquo=
te>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, I added: =E2=80=9CThough: A private=
 credit fund that leverages its fund with short-term borrowing is riskier, =
more run-prone, more like a bank.=E2=80=9D You could imagine private credit=
 being=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>safe, very Chicago-plan, just taking long-te=
rm=C2=A0equity investments from people who want to take risks. But financia=
l markets love leverage, and if you have a $1 billion loan fund, you might =
go to someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Che=
y I have $1 billion of equity, lend me another $1 billion and I=E2=80=99ll =
go make $2 billion of loans with the money.=E2=80=9D And then =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if the money you borrowed from the bank is short-term=C2=A0or subject to=
 margin calls =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have reintroduced a lot of the fragility o=
f banking.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The details matter, though. A good, conservati=
ve, well-run bank might well fund $2=C2=A0billion of long-term loans with $=
200=C2=A0million of equity and $1.8 billion of short-term borrowing (deposi=
ts), which is just a lot more fragile than a private credit fund=C2=A0fundi=
ng them with $1 billion of equity and $1 billion of borrowing. Even if the =
bank is making safer and more conservative loans than the private credit fu=
nd, it might be more fragile.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway also yesterday the Fed released its <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31427429.263436/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L3B1YmxpY2F0aW9ucy9maWxlcy9maW5hbmNpYWwt=
c3RhYmlsaXR5LXJlcG9ydC0yMDIzMDUwOC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4db25bf9" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Financial Stability Report</a>, and it directly discusses the fina=
ncial-stability risks of private credit funds. The Fed, like me, is not tha=
t worried:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since the 2007=E2=80=9309 financial crisis, pr=
ivate credit funds have experienced substantial growth, as the privately ne=
gotiated loans that they extend have become an increasingly important sourc=
e of credit for some businesses, particularly middle-market companies.=C2=
=A0As of 2021:Q4, their assets under management (AUM) stood at $1=C2=A0tril=
lion, and the estimated =E2=80=9Cdry powder=E2=80=9D (committed but uncalle=
d capital) amounted to $228=C2=A0billion (figure A). =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors in private credit funds are diversif=
ied institutional investors and high-net-worth individuals (figure B). Base=
d on Form PF, as of 2021:Q4, public and private pension funds held about 31=
=C2=A0percent ($307=C2=A0billion) of aggregate private credit fund assets. =
Other private funds made up the second-largest cohort of investors at 14=C2=
=A0percent ($136=C2=A0billion) of assets, while insurance companies and ind=
ividual investors each had about 9=C2=A0percent ($92=C2=A0billion). Given t=
he rapid growth of private credit funds, these investors are increasingly i=
ndirectly exposed to the liquidity and credit risks of assets in private cr=
edit fund portfolios.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Financial stability risks associated with inve=
stor redemptions from private credit funds appear low. Most private credit =
funds have a closed-end fund structure and typically lock up the capital of=
 their investors (that is, limited partners) for 5=C2=A0to=C2=A010=C2=A0yea=
rs. Those funds that are structured as hedge funds routinely restrict share=
 redemptions of their investors through redemption notice periods, lockups,=
 and gates. Thus, private credit funds engage in limited liquidity and matu=
rity transformation. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Risks to financial stability from leverage at =
private credit funds appear low. Indeed, most private credit funds are unle=
vered, with no borrowings or derivative exposures. A minority of funds, how=
ever, use modest amounts of financial or synthetic leverage. Figure C shows=
 that the most levered funds (those at the 95th percentile) have borrowings=
-to-assets ratios of about 1.27 and derivatives-to-assets ratios of about 0=
.66. In the aggregate, private credit funds borrowed about $200 billion in =
2021:Q4, mainly from U.S. financial institutions, and held about $200 billi=
on of derivative gross notional exposure. Risks to lenders of private credi=
t funds, typically banks, appear moderate due to the relatively modest amou=
nt of borrowings of private credit funds and their secured nature.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Overall, the financial stability vulnerabiliti=
es posed by private credit funds appear limited. Most private credit funds =
use little leverage and have low redemption risks, making it unlikely that =
these funds would amplify market stress through asset sales.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Are private credit funds making worse loans th=
an banks are? Just the wrong question to ask! The right question is =E2=80=
=9Ccan there be a run on private credit funds,=E2=80=9D and the answer, so =
far, is =E2=80=9Cmostly no.=E2=80=9D</p>
